"""
rel_disturb — STRAW-lite read-disturb reclaim (design doc §5, design §9 L6).

Extends, does NOT duplicate, the existing FTL counter: the firmware already
bumps `rd_disturb[blk]` on every read (ftl.spl:29,109,117,347-362) and gates
the existing `scrub_once` at `READ_DISTURB_THRESHOLD` (50, nvme_types.spl:43).
This module consumes that counter as a caller-supplied OBSERVATION (source of
truth, never copied) and adds ONLY a hottest-page estimate — a parallel stress
counter would diverge from `rd_disturb` over time.

The hottest page is tracked with a Boyer-Moore majority-candidate: O(1) per
observation, no `Dict`, no per-page array — a cheap proxy for "one wordline is
taking most of the read stress" from the page index the FTL read path already
knows (ppn_page(ppn) once L8 wires this in).

Contract: doc/05_design/hardware/nand_recovery/recovery_algorithms_design.md
§5 (pseudocode implemented verbatim below) + design §9 L6 ("consumes existing
rd_disturb", depends on L1 only). Pure-policy leaf: `use nvme_types.*` +
`use nd_types.*` + `use rel_types.*` ONLY — never fil/ftl (design §0 /
architecture LAW: fil.spl and ftl.spl import the rel_* leaves, never the
reverse). No module holds a Fil/Ftl handle; `rel_disturb_due` returns a pure
`RelAction` verdict and the FTL mounting layer actuates (`scrub_once`).

Language landmines honored (design §0):
- Return-the-object: `rel_disturb_observe`/`rel_disturb_clear` return the
  updated `RelDisturbState`; callers reassign (arrays are value types, passed
  by copy).
- No Dict: per-block state is `RelDisturbState`'s dense `[i64]` arrays
  (rel_types.spl, length NUM_BLOCKS = 64), indexed by physical block.
- Constants are fn-returning literals, never module-level scalars (matches the
  sibling `rel_act_*` constants in rel_types.spl — freestanding-safe habit).

Typed-dimensions law (guide "TYPED DIMENSIONS LAW", rel_types.spl docstring):
`blk`/`page` are NdBlock/NdPage newtypes (nd_types.spl) at every fn's scalar
boundary; converted to raw i64 immediately at the array-index / RelAction.arg
flat boundary — the dense `[i64]` arrays themselves stay `[i64]` (the block is
the ARRAY INDEX, a flat i64; the stored values are page-index/count
estimates), matching rel_types.spl's own note on RelDisturbState.

Boyer-Moore majority-vote semantics (design §5, verbatim pseudocode below):
this is a STREAMING MAJORITY-CANDIDATE estimator, not an exact top-page
counter. Classic Boyer-Moore property: IF a true majority page exists in the
observed stream (strictly more than half the reads), the candidate at the end
IS that page. If no true majority exists, the algorithm is still fully
DETERMINISTIC (no randomness, no hashing) but the surviving candidate is
whatever page happened to out-cancel the others along that specific sequence —
documented in the design doc as "the majority-vote hottest page is an estimate
that can miss multi-hot-page patterns" (§5 "Does NOT do in v1"). This is by
design, not a bug: rel_disturb_due never treats a non-majority candidate as
authoritative on its own — it only fires reclaim when hot_count crosses
REL_DISTURB_HOTPAGE_MIN (a concentration signal), layered on top of the
existing rd_disturb block-level gate which is the primary, always-correct
source of truth.
"""

use nvme_types.*
use nd_types.*
use rel_types.*

# REL_DISTURB_HOTPAGE_MIN (design §5 constants table): fires before the
# block-wide rd_disturb count reaches READ_DISTURB_THRESHOLD (50) when a
# single page dominates -- concentrates reclaim on an actually-stressed block
# earlier without churning evenly-read blocks. fn-returning literal per the
# repo's freestanding-safe constant convention (matches rel_act_* in
# rel_types.spl); the design doc's pseudocode spells this REL_DISTURB_HOTPAGE_MIN().
fn rel_disturb_hotpage_min() -> i64:
    40

# One read event on (blk, page): Boyer-Moore majority-vote update (design §5,
# implemented verbatim). Return-the-object: caller reassigns.
fn rel_disturb_observe(st: RelDisturbState, blk: NdBlock, page: NdPage) -> RelDisturbState:
    var out: RelDisturbState = st
    val b: i64 = blk.idx
    val p: i64 = page.idx
    if out.hot_count[b] == 0:
        out.hot_page[b] = p
        out.hot_count[b] = 1
    elif out.hot_page[b] == p:
        out.hot_count[b] = out.hot_count[b] + 1
    else:
        out.hot_count[b] = out.hot_count[b] - 1
    return out

# Reclaim verdict (design §5, implemented verbatim). Two independent gates,
# either one fires ReclaimNow:
#   1. block-wide `rd_disturb_blk` gate — the EXISTING scrub_once threshold,
#      preserved unchanged (caller passes ftl.spl's live rd_disturb[blk]; this
#      module never copies or re-derives that counter).
#   2. hottest-page gate — a single page dominating this block's Boyer-Moore
#      candidate count, which can fire earlier than gate 1.
fn rel_disturb_due(st: RelDisturbState, blk: NdBlock, rd_disturb_blk: i64) -> RelAction:
    val b: i64 = blk.idx
    if rd_disturb_blk > READ_DISTURB_THRESHOLD:
        return rel_action(rel_act_reclaim(), b)
    if st.hot_count[b] > rel_disturb_hotpage_min():
        return rel_action(rel_act_reclaim(), b)
    return rel_action(rel_act_accept(), 0)

# Clear exactly one block's hottest-page estimate — called on erase/reclaim
# (design §5). Return-the-object: caller reassigns.
fn rel_disturb_clear(st: RelDisturbState, blk: NdBlock) -> RelDisturbState:
    var out: RelDisturbState = st
    val b: i64 = blk.idx
    out.hot_page[b] = 0
    out.hot_count[b] = 0
    return out
